        "content": "type: search_result\ntitle: JavaScript Event Loop Explained (With Examples) 2026 | Crosscheck - Visual Bug Reporting Tool\nurl: \"https://crosscheck.cloud/blogs/javascript-event-loop-explained/\"\ndescription: \"JavaScript event loop explained with code walkthroughs — call stack, queues, microtasks vs macrotasks, async/await, and Node.js phases. Read the breakdown.\"\npage_age: 3 weeks ago\nprofile_name: Crosscheck\nmeta_url_favicon: \"https://imgs.search.brave.com/WOfVvSXYzbBF7_pkunKiZHahUAEILAJ89Kj0AWX2uyg/rs:fit:32:32:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cDovL2Zhdmlj/b25zLnNlYXJjaC5i/cmF2ZS5jb20vaWNv/bnMvMTY3ZmM0YzNk/OGRjMWZiNDFiMmVk/Yzc1MDcwNzFjOTU5/NWZkYmZhNGNiOGZh/YTUyMTY5MjU0NjEw/ODk1NjE1Yi9jcm9z/c2NoZWNrLmNsb3Vk/Lw\"\nthumbnail_src: \"https://imgs.search.brave.com/BnqcbS2GvL946hVowxZS7udlCYwUHOrk-9vTvR9HyBE/rs:fit:200:200:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cHM6Ly9jcm9z/c2NoZWNrLmNsb3Vk/L2Jsb2ctY292ZXJz/L2phdmFzY3JpcHQt/ZXZlbnQtbG9vcC1l/eHBsYWluZWQucG5n\"\nthumbnail_original: \"https://crosscheck.cloud/blog-covers/javascript-event-loop-explained.png\"\nextra_snippets: \"The JavaScript event loop is the runtime mechanism that lets single-threaded JavaScript handle asynchronous work without blocking. It moves callbacks between four actors — the call stack, the web APIs (or Node APIs), the macrotask queue, and the microtask queue — in a strict, repeatable order.|The danger of nextTick is recursion — a chain of nextTick callbacks that schedules more nextTick callbacks will starve the event loop entirely. The Node docs recommend setImmediate for any genuinely recursive deferral. Deno uses V8 and Tokio, with the same microtask semantics as Node, exposes setImmediate/process.nextTick for compatibility, and otherwise behaves like a browser-style loop. Bun is written in Zig on top of JavaScriptCore (not V8) and uses its own event-loop implementation rather than libuv.|JavaScript runs one thing at a time on the call stack — async APIs hand work to the browser or Node, then push a callback into a queue when they finish. Microtasks (Promise.then, queueMicrotask, MutationObserver) drain completely between every macrotask, including between individual timer callbacks. Macrotasks (setTimeout, setInterval, I/O, setImmediate, MessageChannel) run one per loop turn.|Call stack. The list of function calls currently executing. JavaScript runs whatever sits on top. When a function returns, its frame pops off. When the stack is empty, the loop is allowed to schedule something new.\"\nhash: 62cf4e188b3fa8cb\nembed_ref: crosscheck.cloud-tST\napp_id: web\nskill_id: search",
